ut 1324":"about 1324","after March 1355":"after March 1355","Of Waterton,Isle of Axholme,Lincs,England":"Haxey, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Waterton, Lincolnshire, England (United Kingdom)":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Womersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Womersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Newmarch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: locative name from Neufmarché (Seine-Maritime). See   Anglo-Norman Families  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Newmark","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Emanuel, Chayim, Meyer, Shlomo, Vigdor.","Americanized form of Scandinavian <b>Nymark</b>: habitational name from farms named with <i>ny</i> ‘new’ + <i>mark</i> ‘field’.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Neumark  ."]},{"name":"Anglo-Norman Families","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from any of the places in Normandy, Picardy, and Artois named (Le)  <i>Quesnay</i> or  <i>Quesnoy</i>, or elsewhere in N France named ( <i>Le</i> or  <i>La</i>)  <i>Chesnay</i> or  <i>Chesnoy</i>. The Domesday Book under-tenant came from Le Quesnay in Seine-Maritime (see   Anglo-Norman Families  ). The place-names all derive from Old French  <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent  <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (Medieval Latin  <i>casnetum</i>)."]},{"name":"Newmarsh","meanings":["Norman:  see  Newmarch  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Newmarch was born in 1314, in Womersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Matilda of Yorkshire. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with William Waterton. She died in 1366, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1314–1366":"1314–1366","1295–1349":"1295–1349","1320–1381":"1320–1381","1300–1353":"1300–1353","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1330–1424":"1330–1424","1272–1355":"1272–1355","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","ABT 1326":"umbes 1326","1272":"1272","1381":"1381","1349":"1349","1326":"1326","1314":"1314","1424":"1424","1324":"1324","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1300":"1300","1353":"1353","1320":"1320","about 1324":"umbes 1324","after March 1355":"pärast märtsi 1355","Of Waterton,Isle of Axholme,Lincs,England":"Haxey, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Waterton, Lincolnshire, England (United Kingdom)":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Womersley, Yo